WEBVTT

00:01.671 --> 00:09.809
♪♪

00:09.844 --> 00:18.191
♪♪

00:18.226 --> 00:26.364
♪♪

00:26.399 --> 00:34.537
♪♪

00:34.572 --> 00:42.710
♪♪

00:42.745 --> 00:46.186
-I'm thinking of
the incredible breakthrough

00:46.221 --> 00:50.586
which has been made possible by
developments in communications,

00:50.621 --> 00:53.589
particularly the transistor
and above all,

00:53.624 --> 00:56.295
the communications satellite.

00:56.330 --> 00:58.561
These things will
make possible a world

00:58.596 --> 01:01.399
in which we can be in instant
contact with each other,

01:01.434 --> 01:04.567
wherever we may be.

01:04.602 --> 01:06.734
It will be possible in that age,

01:06.769 --> 01:08.835
perhaps only 50 years from now,

01:08.870 --> 01:13.675
for a man to conduct
his business from Tahiti or Bali

01:13.710 --> 01:17.382
just as well
as he could from London.

01:17.417 --> 01:19.450
In fact,
if it proves worthwhile,

01:19.485 --> 01:22.189
almost any executive skill,

01:22.224 --> 01:24.224
any administrative skill,

01:24.259 --> 01:26.226
even any physical skill,

01:26.261 --> 01:30.230
could be made
independent of distance.

01:30.265 --> 01:31.858
When that time comes,

01:31.893 --> 01:34.630
the whole world will have
shrunk to a point.

01:34.665 --> 01:37.303
And the traditional role
of the city

01:37.338 --> 01:39.503
as a meeting place for man

01:39.538 --> 01:42.737
would have ceased to make
any sense.

01:42.772 --> 01:45.641
In fact, men will
no longer commute.

01:45.676 --> 01:47.412
They will communicate.

01:47.447 --> 01:52.450
♪♪

01:52.485 --> 01:58.522
♪♪

01:58.557 --> 02:00.821
-Fuck's sake.
-We're not late!

02:00.856 --> 02:02.757
-No, I know,
but I'm going to throw up.

02:02.792 --> 02:04.561
-Okay.

02:11.999 --> 02:13.834
Shit!

02:23.978 --> 02:27.419
<i>-Matt Sundin is the sleepiest</i>
<i>of all out there.</i>

02:27.454 --> 02:31.192
<i>He's proven NHL talent but not</i>
<i>scoring like the Leafs need --</i>

02:44.999 --> 02:46.966
-Your 9:00 is here.
-Where's Brock?

02:47.001 --> 02:48.737
-His office.
-Mr. Balsillie?

02:48.772 --> 02:51.443
You wanted to see this report.
-Talk to Shelly.

03:08.858 --> 03:11.430
-[Muttering]
Integrated circuits...

03:11.465 --> 03:13.828
-Well, I finally understand
that quote,

03:13.863 --> 03:16.633
When you grow up,
your heart dies.

03:19.605 --> 03:22.375
That's from "Breakfast Club."
John Hughes.

03:22.410 --> 03:23.937
-Do you hear that?

03:23.972 --> 03:26.874
[Low hiss]

03:26.909 --> 03:29.712
-Uh, yeah.

03:29.747 --> 03:31.549
You talk about that buzzing?
-Mm.

03:31.584 --> 03:34.354
-It's an office, I'm sure they
got a million little buzzes.

03:34.389 --> 03:35.982
-Mm.
-It's a subtle buzzing.

03:41.825 --> 03:44.991
-There.
-You've identified it.

03:45.026 --> 03:49.028
-Mm.
-What?

03:49.063 --> 03:53.670
Made in China --
the mark of the beast?

03:57.940 --> 04:02.041
[Hissing distorts]
Uh... Um...

04:02.076 --> 04:03.812
Mike?
-I can't concentrate.

04:03.847 --> 04:05.715
-And so what?
Are you going to fix this?

04:05.750 --> 04:08.751
-I'm going to fix it.
-Uh, now's not the time.

04:08.786 --> 04:10.687
The meeting starts in,
like, two minutes.

04:10.722 --> 04:11.919
Now's not the time.
Now's not the time.

04:11.954 --> 04:13.327
Now's not the time.
-Okay?

04:13.362 --> 04:14.922
I need, like, a paper clip.

04:14.957 --> 04:18.926
-That's a guy's thing.
That's a guy's fucking thing.

04:22.030 --> 04:24.635
-It has no off switch.
That means it's always on.

04:24.670 --> 04:26.868
So it's just always buzzing.
-Uh-huh. Yeah.

04:26.903 --> 04:31.004
Um... Well,

04:31.039 --> 04:34.876
Yeah, go fast.

04:34.911 --> 04:36.647
-You can tell him he's
not going -- [chuckles] --

04:36.682 --> 04:38.946
He's not going to get steel.

04:38.981 --> 04:41.949
Alloys, Harry!

04:41.984 --> 04:44.754
I'll call you back.

04:44.789 --> 04:47.592
-They're outside.

04:47.627 --> 04:49.792
-These guys really
are Dutch, huh?

04:49.827 --> 04:52.663
-[Chuckles]

04:52.698 --> 04:56.436
Listen, Rick, I've thought
about this a lot.

04:56.471 --> 04:58.834
And if these guys take the deal,

04:58.869 --> 05:01.067
I want to run the new division.

05:12.113 --> 05:14.652
-Think you can run this place?

05:14.687 --> 05:17.589
-Yes! Yes!

05:17.624 --> 05:18.986
-Me too.

05:22.024 --> 05:26.158
Just so we're clear,
if this thing doesn't go,

05:26.193 --> 05:29.436
we never had this conversation.

05:29.471 --> 05:31.570
-Great. Great. Um...

05:34.608 --> 05:36.377
-Thank you.

05:38.040 --> 05:40.744
-There's one adjustment.

05:40.779 --> 05:42.108
Apparently the Americans
offered them

05:42.143 --> 05:44.616
some fancy tax splitting plan,

05:44.651 --> 05:47.553
so we need to show them
the Canadian version.

05:47.588 --> 05:48.851
-I don't have that.
-No, no.

05:48.886 --> 05:50.424
-Callahan worked
something up last minute.

05:50.459 --> 05:54.461
We're going to bring him in
to explain it.

05:54.496 --> 05:57.794
-Callahan.
Uh...

05:57.829 --> 06:00.060
You know what?
I think that's a bad idea.

06:00.095 --> 06:02.964
-Why is that?

06:02.999 --> 06:05.670
-I tell you what, Rick,
why don't you have

06:05.705 --> 06:07.067
Callahan explain
the tax thing to me

06:07.102 --> 06:08.673
and I'll just -- I'll work it
into my pitch.

06:08.708 --> 06:11.038
I think that's better.
-Kyle was up all night

06:11.073 --> 06:13.172
putting this together
as a favor to me.

06:13.207 --> 06:17.616
He gets to present.
-Rick, I mean...

06:17.651 --> 06:19.816
You're going to have
this guy present to Stork?

06:19.851 --> 06:25.118
I mean, he looks like a..
fucking, a total goof.

06:25.153 --> 06:28.528
-Jim...
I'm not asking.

06:28.563 --> 06:36.668
♪♪

06:36.703 --> 06:38.604
-Okay, great.

06:38.639 --> 06:44.137
♪♪

06:44.172 --> 06:47.943
-Okay. Bald, scary looking guy
walking towards us right now.

06:47.978 --> 06:50.011
-God damn it!
-Mike?

06:50.046 --> 06:51.782
-Yeah. Got it.

06:53.654 --> 06:55.555
-Watch the fuck out!
-Oh, shit.

06:55.590 --> 06:57.018
Sit down. Sit down.

06:58.824 --> 07:00.857
-Much better.

07:05.798 --> 07:08.502
-[Sighs]

07:16.303 --> 07:18.105
-Yeah. What can I do for you?

07:18.140 --> 07:19.843
-Yes. Hi.

07:19.878 --> 07:25.244
I'm Mike Lazaridis,
CEO of Research in Motion.

07:25.279 --> 07:27.279
We create various
computer hardware systems

07:27.314 --> 07:29.853
using both custom
design integrated circuits,

07:29.888 --> 07:31.525
as well as off
the shelf components

07:31.560 --> 07:33.989
provided by major hardware
vendors such as Intel,

07:34.024 --> 07:36.563
American Micro Devices
and CYRIX.

07:36.598 --> 07:39.192
Our clients have included
US Robotics,

07:39.227 --> 07:41.095
Rogers Cantel, RAM Mobile.

07:41.130 --> 07:42.734
-Just a second.

07:42.769 --> 07:44.032
[Dialing]

07:49.809 --> 07:52.975
Hey, you're on
Callahan's desk, right?

07:53.010 --> 07:55.010
Okay, great.
This is Jim Balsillie.

07:55.045 --> 07:57.243
Brock wanted me to do
a quick proof of that tax stuff

07:57.278 --> 08:00.917
before the meeting.
Could you bring me a --

08:00.952 --> 08:02.655
Exactly.

08:02.690 --> 08:04.250
Okay, great. Thanks.

08:12.799 --> 08:15.899
Okay, uh, what is this?

08:15.934 --> 08:20.871
-So w-we had a shop teacher...

08:20.906 --> 08:22.972
who told us --
oh, we had a shop teacher

08:23.007 --> 08:24.908
in high school named
Mr. Moshinsky,

08:24.943 --> 08:28.274
who told us the person who puts
a computer inside a phone

08:28.309 --> 08:30.914
will change the world.

08:30.949 --> 08:32.311
Well, we have a plan
to piggyback

08:32.346 --> 08:35.083
on the unused bandwidth
of the UHF spectrum

08:35.118 --> 08:37.591
to create an all
in one mobile device.

08:37.626 --> 08:39.021
[Beep]
<i>-Adam Callahan's assistant</i>

08:39.056 --> 08:41.793
is here to see you?
-Send him in.

08:43.797 --> 08:46.127
Great.
-Sorry, Mr. Balsillie.

08:46.162 --> 08:48.129
No one -- I didn't realize you
needed a copy of

08:48.164 --> 08:50.329
this tax report also --
-I'm in a meeting right now.

08:55.237 --> 08:57.006
Okay.

09:01.683 --> 09:06.752
-So, basically there is
a free

09:06.787 --> 09:10.151
wireless Internet signal
all across North America,

09:10.186 --> 09:13.924
and nobody has figured out
how to use it.

09:13.959 --> 09:17.026
There's free Internet
in this room right now.

09:17.061 --> 09:20.326
-Mm-hmm.

09:20.361 --> 09:24.066
-It's like the force.

09:24.101 --> 09:25.837
Sorry. Have you seen
"Star Wars"?

09:28.039 --> 09:30.776
-No.

09:30.811 --> 09:34.340
-So, okay, picture a pager,

09:34.375 --> 09:39.345
a cell phone and an email
machine, all in one thing.

09:45.991 --> 09:49.795
-We call it, um, Pocket Link.

09:55.429 --> 09:59.365
-Okay, listen, we don't do
anything like that here.

09:59.400 --> 10:01.708
We are a commercial
manufacturing company.

10:01.743 --> 10:04.073
You want to talk
to a VC guy?

10:11.016 --> 10:13.049
And you need a better name.

10:20.861 --> 10:23.125
-You're going to cry?!
Mike!

10:23.160 --> 10:25.457
Oh, it's just disappointment?
-Yeah.

10:25.492 --> 10:28.900
-You did great!
-[Clears throat]

10:28.935 --> 10:33.135
Well, I saw that Rick sent
the limo to pick you guys up.

10:33.170 --> 10:35.940
We must need this merger
worse than I thought.

10:35.975 --> 10:39.075
[Light laughter]

10:39.110 --> 10:40.813
So, I know we have
a lot to cover,

10:40.848 --> 10:45.785
but I thought we should start
with our tax strategy.

10:45.820 --> 10:48.953
Now, I'm sure you heard it
from the Americans,

10:48.988 --> 10:51.219
but let me assure you,
we also know how to

10:51.254 --> 10:53.188
cheat on our taxes
here in Canada.

10:53.223 --> 10:55.729
Okay?

10:55.764 --> 10:57.159
Here's what we can do:

10:57.194 --> 10:59.161
We run payroll out of Ontario,

10:59.196 --> 11:01.064
but we pay all our vendors
from the Netherlands.

11:01.099 --> 11:02.461
We split that fucker
right in half.

11:02.496 --> 11:05.233
The left won't know
what the right is doing.

11:05.268 --> 11:07.433
Plus, we get a nice
little provincial

11:07.468 --> 11:09.336
kickback on manufacturing labor.

11:09.371 --> 11:11.305
We get a massive
federal tax credit

11:11.340 --> 11:14.341
because they don't know whether
they're private or public.

11:14.376 --> 11:23.152
♪♪

11:23.187 --> 11:32.359
♪♪

11:32.394 --> 11:35.868
-Beam me aboard!

11:35.903 --> 11:39.333
-Prisoner, and held captive
within the digital world of

11:39.368 --> 11:41.203
the computer itself.

11:41.238 --> 11:43.007
-♪ Riding on any wave ♪

11:43.042 --> 11:44.976
♪ That is the luck you crave ♪

11:45.011 --> 11:46.912
♪ They don't believe it now ♪

11:46.947 --> 11:48.947
♪ They just think it's stupid ♪

11:48.982 --> 11:50.949
♪ So got anything? ♪

11:50.984 --> 11:52.819
♪ Anyone could have done ♪

11:52.854 --> 11:54.480
♪ Who would've cared at all ♪

11:54.515 --> 11:57.054
♪ Not you ♪

11:57.089 --> 11:59.485
♪ Another heart ♪
-Hello?

11:59.520 --> 12:01.421
-Hello!
-♪ Has made the trade ♪

12:01.456 --> 12:03.896
♪ Forget it, forget it ♪
-So, what you're saying is that

12:03.931 --> 12:05.931
you just touch and talk?
-♪ I don't understand ♪

12:05.966 --> 12:08.098
♪ How a heart is a spade ♪

12:08.133 --> 12:12.300
♪ But somehow the vital
connection is made ♪

12:12.335 --> 12:15.534
-You can use your cellular phone
to order me a pizza.

12:15.569 --> 12:17.877
-And that includes
50 minutes of air time.

12:17.912 --> 12:20.374
-We'll page you.
-Well, it's very hip to be

12:20.409 --> 12:23.916
on the Internet right now.
-[Both shouting]

12:23.951 --> 12:25.511
-I still think
Apple has a future.

12:25.546 --> 12:28.514
The way out is not to slash
and burn, it's to innovate.

12:28.549 --> 12:30.318
♪Riding on anything ♪

12:30.353 --> 12:32.122
♪ Anything's good enough ♪

12:32.157 --> 12:34.091
♪ Who would've thought it of ♪

12:34.126 --> 12:35.158
[Engages parking brake]

12:35.193 --> 12:37.127
-Oh, okay. Here's what I think.

12:37.162 --> 12:39.998
Mike, super simple.
Hit him with the good news,

12:40.033 --> 12:42.935
bad news routine --
good news, bad news routine.

12:42.970 --> 12:46.972
All right? You're going to
say good -- Mike?!

12:47.007 --> 12:50.008
What?

12:50.043 --> 12:51.405
Everything's going to be fine.

12:51.440 --> 12:53.275
We still have
the US Robotics deal.

12:53.310 --> 12:55.541
We're like, what did
the cave say about Aladdin,

12:55.576 --> 12:57.213
"Diamond in the rough"?
Fuck!

12:57.248 --> 13:01.151
-What?
-I forgot the easel.

13:01.186 --> 13:03.252
-No, we have to change the name.
Product needs a new name.

13:03.287 --> 13:05.089
-You're giving that guy
way too much credit, man.

13:05.124 --> 13:07.157
He hasn't seen "Star Wars."
He's bald.

13:07.192 --> 13:10.457
How much you want to bet they
don't even mention the phone.

13:10.492 --> 13:14.065
[Typing, laughter]

13:14.100 --> 13:16.331
-Are you office dad?
-[Laughter]

13:16.366 --> 13:20.071
-Dude. Okay.
Make a make a -- make a thing.

13:20.106 --> 13:22.238
Make a "Scott sucks" --
-I can't.

13:22.273 --> 13:25.439
That's why I'm using
your computer.

13:25.474 --> 13:27.507
-21 boy Canada.

13:27.542 --> 13:29.883
-That's me.

13:29.918 --> 13:32.380
This guy's telling me
about sniffing his --

13:32.415 --> 13:34.514
Sniffing his --
[Door opens]

13:36.650 --> 13:38.419
-Did they buy the phone?

13:40.654 --> 13:44.425
-So, we've got good news
and bad news.

13:48.332 --> 13:51.069
The -- okay,
the bad news is that,

13:51.104 --> 13:55.040
yeah, the presentation,
we were not heard,

13:55.075 --> 13:57.306
and they did not understand
the product,

13:57.341 --> 13:59.506
and so
they did not buy the phone.

14:02.247 --> 14:06.447
-What was the good news?
-What's the good news?

14:06.482 --> 14:10.319
-Emergency movie night,
right now, Steven Spielberg's

14:10.354 --> 14:13.927
"Raiders of the Lost Ark,"
letterbox.

14:13.962 --> 14:16.424
-No way!
-Shotgun. Shotgun. Shotgun.

14:16.459 --> 14:19.295
Shotgun!

14:19.330 --> 14:21.231
-You said their headpiece
only had markings on one side.

14:21.266 --> 14:23.299
Are you absolutely sure?

14:25.006 --> 14:27.468
Balloq's staff is too long.

14:27.503 --> 14:29.943
[All] "We're digging in
the wrong place"!

14:29.978 --> 14:32.242
[Laughter]

14:32.277 --> 14:34.343
[Dramatic music]

14:34.378 --> 14:35.949
-Don't!

14:40.219 --> 14:43.319
-[All] "Bad dates."
-Bad dates.

14:43.354 --> 14:46.619
-Couple of bad dates.
-A couple bad dates!

14:46.654 --> 14:49.490
Couple bad dates!
-That was -- that was there.

14:49.525 --> 14:52.493
Why did they go the other way?
That was like that...

14:52.528 --> 14:57.267
♪♪

14:57.302 --> 15:01.139
-Mike, you're missing
your favorite movie, man!

15:01.174 --> 15:07.607
♪♪

15:07.642 --> 15:14.284
♪♪

15:14.319 --> 15:20.752
♪♪

15:20.787 --> 15:27.429
♪♪

15:27.464 --> 15:30.696
-[Sighs]

15:30.731 --> 15:39.045
♪♪

15:39.080 --> 15:47.152
♪♪

15:47.187 --> 15:50.716
<i>-Toronto wins it by a count</i>
<i>of 5 to 4.</i>

15:50.751 --> 15:53.191
<i>Doug Gilmour adds three assists</i>
<i>to his five</i>

15:53.226 --> 15:55.490
<i>to finish the game with 30....</i>

15:55.525 --> 15:57.096
<i>...in the extra period.</i>

15:57.131 --> 15:59.296
<i>But obviously the story was --</i>

15:59.331 --> 16:01.100
[Kills engine]

16:01.135 --> 16:02.563
-Are they top or bottom left?

16:02.598 --> 16:04.367
-Go, I got my whole group.

16:04.402 --> 16:05.731
-Send -- Send everything.
Top left.

16:05.766 --> 16:07.535
Let's take.
Let's take a gamble.

16:07.570 --> 16:09.504
We'll go for Scott.
-Does anybody have

16:09.539 --> 16:11.506
a type-c coax?
-They don't even know

16:11.541 --> 16:13.772
I'm not even top left.
-Scott, you're attacking me.

16:13.807 --> 16:15.411
-What?
-You're attacking me.

16:15.446 --> 16:17.611
-Oh, I'm sorry.
-Send the dogs, Ethan,

16:17.646 --> 16:19.547
Send the dogs.
They're rushing.

16:19.582 --> 16:21.549
-Bottom right.
-I'm sending another. Another.

16:21.584 --> 16:23.287
-They got rockets.
I got to run down.

16:23.322 --> 16:25.223
-Anybody have any type c
coax cables?

16:25.258 --> 16:28.226
-Kiss it bye-bye!
-Oh, the plunger is moving!

16:28.261 --> 16:30.162
-No!
-The plunger is moving!

16:30.197 --> 16:34.100
Dude, come on.
[Ringing]

16:34.135 --> 16:36.069
-No! No!
[Bang]

16:36.104 --> 16:38.665
-Ow! Ow!

16:38.700 --> 16:41.602
-Oh!
-I'm sorry, boys!

16:41.637 --> 16:45.606
But it's back!
It's back!

16:45.641 --> 16:48.081
-You had them --
-It's back!

16:48.116 --> 16:50.248
-[Clears throat]

16:57.455 --> 16:59.686
-Thank you.
-Thank you so much.

16:59.721 --> 17:01.655
-Nothing for me.
Thanks.

17:01.690 --> 17:03.855
So I know
how to sell your phone.

17:03.890 --> 17:07.166
I know how to market it, and I
know who we can sell it to.

17:07.201 --> 17:11.467
-Who?
-What do you mean, we?

17:11.502 --> 17:13.106
-Here's the deal.

17:13.141 --> 17:15.240
I will leave my job
at Sutherland Schultz.

17:15.275 --> 17:18.738
If you make me CEO
of Research in Motion.

17:21.248 --> 17:23.644
-Are you serious?

17:23.679 --> 17:26.548
-That was the worst product
pitch I've ever seen in my life.

17:26.583 --> 17:28.715
You guys don't stand
a chance out there.

17:28.750 --> 17:30.816
You need me.

17:30.851 --> 17:34.226
-Sorry. I don't know
who you think you are,

17:34.261 --> 17:37.196
but we are just fine.

17:37.231 --> 17:40.364
We have a $16 million
deal with US Robotics.

17:40.399 --> 17:42.828
-16 million?
-That's right.

17:42.863 --> 17:46.535
-Wow. Okay.
And what did they buy?

17:46.570 --> 17:49.637
-Modems.
Ever heard of them?

17:49.672 --> 17:52.673
-Are they like the force
in "Star Wars"?

17:52.708 --> 17:56.644
-Very funny. You know,
your logo literally is SS.

17:56.679 --> 18:00.483
-And how much have they paid you
on that $16 million?

18:00.518 --> 18:02.551
-Yeah. Nothing.
-Zero?

18:02.586 --> 18:04.916
-Nothing yet.
We haven't delivered the modems.

18:04.951 --> 18:07.721
-Well, we shipped them
product samples months ago,

18:07.756 --> 18:10.724
and their accounting department
won't even return

18:10.759 --> 18:12.429
our phone calls.
-Yeah, but they're gonna --

18:12.464 --> 18:14.167
What's going on?
They're going to pay us.

18:14.202 --> 18:16.268
We have a $16 million deal
with US Robotics.

18:16.303 --> 18:18.732
-Yeah, so, uh, you guys are
getting fucked.

18:18.767 --> 18:21.702
-Why would you -- why do you
think -- why do you say that?

18:21.737 --> 18:23.605
-Well, because I would
do the same thing.

18:23.640 --> 18:25.409
Little operation like yours.

18:25.444 --> 18:26.905
They know they can
withhold payment

18:26.940 --> 18:29.215
till the last possible second
and then crush you.

18:29.250 --> 18:31.580
These guys, they're...
They're pirates.

18:31.615 --> 18:33.318
-Uh-huh...

18:35.256 --> 18:39.489
-We got it. Thank you.
Um...

18:39.524 --> 18:41.458
How do you know anything --

18:41.493 --> 18:44.824
What the fuck do I care?
How much money do you got?

18:50.634 --> 18:52.766
-Yeah, um...

18:52.801 --> 18:54.504
-Okay, guys?

18:54.539 --> 18:56.605
-2.50?
-Here's what I'm going to do.

18:56.640 --> 19:00.213
I will give you
$20,000 cash today.

19:00.248 --> 19:03.249
I'll sell the phone, I'll work
out this problem with USR.

19:03.284 --> 19:07.781
But I want 50% of the company,
and I've got to be CEO.

19:12.755 --> 19:14.722
-That's...
-Are you joking?

19:14.757 --> 19:17.890
No. Obviously. Obviously.
No. No!

19:17.925 --> 19:19.958
-Should I just --
-Mike?

19:19.993 --> 19:22.796
-Okay. Okay.
-Who is in charge here?

19:22.831 --> 19:24.732
-Oh, I mean, technically --
-Mike is in charge,

19:24.767 --> 19:26.470
and he says no.

19:32.742 --> 19:35.347
-I am in charge.

19:35.382 --> 19:37.877
And I say...

19:37.912 --> 19:39.813
-Sorry.

19:39.848 --> 19:41.650
-You don't need to do
what this guy says.

19:41.685 --> 19:43.289
We just met him.
He's not your dad!

19:43.324 --> 19:44.455
-Okay...

19:50.364 --> 19:53.629
-Thanks. Thank you.

19:57.800 --> 19:59.965
-Very sassy man.

20:00.000 --> 20:01.406
Wouldn't you say?

20:01.441 --> 20:05.036
He had a --
He had a sass.

20:05.071 --> 20:07.313
-"Modems, ever heard of those,"
or whatever, like --

20:07.348 --> 20:10.415
-Oh, no. I sassed him too,
but he sassed me back.

20:12.419 --> 20:16.520
Like, what's he trying to say?
We don't have our modem deal?

20:16.555 --> 20:19.358
[Laughs]

20:19.393 --> 20:24.594
[Video game sound effects,
line ringing]

20:24.629 --> 20:26.827
<i>-US Robotics.</i>
<i>How may I direct your call?</i>

20:26.862 --> 20:28.829
-Yeah, it's Mike Lazaridis
from Research in Motion.

20:28.864 --> 20:30.699
We're actually building
some circuit boards

20:30.734 --> 20:32.371
for you guys.
<i>-One moment please.</i>

20:32.406 --> 20:39.543
[Beeping]

20:39.578 --> 20:42.414
<i>-Mike! Is that you?</i>
-Yes, hi.

20:42.449 --> 20:46.616
I was just wondering if --
if it would all --

20:46.651 --> 20:51.016
be at all possible for us to
invoice you

20:51.051 --> 20:53.854
for the first half or third

20:53.889 --> 20:57.495
of our -- your order
from us, if -- if --

20:57.530 --> 21:01.433
can -- can we invoice you
for some some of our --

21:01.468 --> 21:05.965
your order.
<i>-[Laughing] Oh, what?</i>

21:06.000 --> 21:08.033
<i>What?</i>
-If that's okay?

21:08.068 --> 21:10.068
<i>-Did you not get my fax?</i>

21:10.103 --> 21:12.774
-We don't have a fax machine.

21:12.809 --> 21:17.647
<i>-Mike, those modems</i>
<i>you sent us back in March,</i>

21:17.682 --> 21:21.453
<i>they were defective.</i>
-I'm sorry. What?

21:21.488 --> 21:23.653
<i>-Yeah, they didn't work.</i>

21:23.688 --> 21:25.391
<i>We had to cancel</i>
<i>the whole order.</i>

21:25.426 --> 21:27.591
<i>But this was months ago, buddy.</i>

21:29.056 --> 21:31.727
<i>I really thought you guys</i>
<i>had a fax machine.</i>

21:31.762 --> 21:34.895
<i>Hey, I tell you what, why don't</i>
<i>you let me make it up to you?</i>

21:34.930 --> 21:38.096
<i>I'll have USR send you one</i>
<i>free of charge on me. Okay?</i>

21:38.131 --> 21:41.539
-Um... Yeah. Okay. Thanks.

21:41.574 --> 21:44.509
<i>-Great. Okay, well,</i>
<i>good luck, Mike.</i>

21:44.544 --> 21:46.445
-Yeah.
<i>-Bye-bye.</i>

21:46.480 --> 21:47.512
-Bye.

21:47.547 --> 21:51.450
♪♪

21:51.485 --> 21:55.388
♪♪

21:55.423 --> 21:59.117
♪♪

21:59.152 --> 22:03.055
♪♪

22:03.090 --> 22:06.465
-What?

22:06.500 --> 22:09.094
Here's what you got to do:
You got to call him back,

22:09.129 --> 22:10.667
you got to
"Glengarry Glen Ross" this guy.

22:10.702 --> 22:13.406
You got to grind him.

22:13.441 --> 22:16.101
-Yeah...
I don't think I can grind him.

22:16.136 --> 22:17.707
-This is exactly what that
Rolex guy said

22:17.742 --> 22:19.445
was going to happen, right?

22:19.480 --> 22:21.073
He predicted it!
What did he say?

22:21.108 --> 22:23.878
He said US Robotics are pirates.

22:23.913 --> 22:26.144
He was fucking dead on.

22:26.179 --> 22:27.981
-Yeah.

22:31.118 --> 22:34.625
[Interference on line]
All right.

22:36.464 --> 22:38.563
-Hey, Steve? Steve?
-Yeah?

22:38.598 --> 22:40.191
-I need the phone line.

22:40.226 --> 22:44.162
-Some guy is trying to say
Noonian Soong is a Q.

22:44.197 --> 22:45.603
-Thank -- yep, thanks.

22:45.638 --> 22:47.638
-All right.
-What are you doing?

22:50.940 --> 22:53.974
-I think we should
take this deal.

22:54.009 --> 22:55.448
-No!

22:55.483 --> 22:56.614
No --

22:56.649 --> 22:58.110
So...

22:58.145 --> 23:00.211
You don't get into business
with people like this.

23:00.246 --> 23:03.181
That guy is sketchy.
-I think he's...

23:03.216 --> 23:05.722
I don't think he's sketchy.

23:05.757 --> 23:10.826
-His business card
is literally sketched out.

23:14.194 --> 23:16.194
The guy's a shark.

23:16.229 --> 23:17.899
-Okay. Do you know...

23:17.934 --> 23:20.770
Do you know who's
afraid of sharks?

23:22.774 --> 23:24.543
Pirates.

23:33.620 --> 23:35.983
Um, so, uh...

23:37.690 --> 23:42.924
We've been talking here,
and we --

23:42.959 --> 23:45.058
We would like to make
a counteroffer.

23:45.093 --> 23:48.963
-You came crawling back
like bugs, like grubs.

23:48.998 --> 23:55.200
-Yeah. So, we would like
to offer you...

23:55.235 --> 23:58.940
10% for...

23:58.975 --> 24:01.008
$500,000.

24:01.043 --> 24:02.680
-Are you out
of your fucking mind?!

24:02.715 --> 24:04.550
I look at 100,000 deals a day!

24:04.585 --> 24:06.244
I pick one!
Is that the quote?

24:06.279 --> 24:10.721
No. I look at 100 deals a day!
I pick one! "Wall Street."

24:10.756 --> 24:15.759
-Okay, uh, w--
uh...

24:15.794 --> 24:18.564
25% for $250,000.

24:18.599 --> 24:20.731
-50% for 50 bucks!

24:20.766 --> 24:24.295
-33% for $125,000,

24:24.330 --> 24:27.573
and you can
run the company with me.

24:27.608 --> 24:31.170
-Mike? No! No!
Yes. Deal. Deal.

24:31.205 --> 24:34.008
-Okay.
-Easy. Dude.

24:37.948 --> 24:40.685
It's going to be
totally fine.

24:40.720 --> 24:44.623
You're going to negotiate
this guy to death.

24:46.088 --> 24:54.567
[Hockey broadcast on television]

24:54.602 --> 24:56.701
<i>-Score!</i>

25:01.070 --> 25:04.269
[Telephone rings]

25:04.304 --> 25:05.809
-Yeah?
-Hi, Jim.

25:05.844 --> 25:08.713
It's Mike Lazaridis
from Research in Motion.

25:08.748 --> 25:11.012
We met at the office
the other day.

25:19.660 --> 25:23.596
So, we'd like
to offer you...

25:23.631 --> 25:27.259
33% of our company for $125,000,

25:27.294 --> 25:31.131
and you and I would be co-CEOs.

25:33.707 --> 25:35.773
<i>-...period.</i>
<i>Couple of them are suspect.</i>

25:35.808 --> 25:38.336
<i>That's their eighth shot of</i>
<i>this hockey game in 6:44.</i>

25:38.371 --> 25:40.712
-Sure.
<i>-That's an improvement.</i>

25:50.284 --> 25:52.086
-Deal.

25:55.223 --> 25:58.092
-Awesome!
Awesome! Dude!

25:58.127 --> 26:02.327
Mike! Scott! Scott?
He did it!

26:02.362 --> 26:03.999
-What do you mean?

26:04.034 --> 26:05.737
-Have you not heard anything
that's been going on

26:05.772 --> 26:07.838
in this room?

26:07.873 --> 26:13.646
♪♪

26:13.681 --> 26:19.245
♪♪

26:19.280 --> 26:25.020
♪♪

26:25.055 --> 26:30.828
♪♪

26:30.863 --> 26:32.291
-You can have,
like, two minutes

26:32.326 --> 26:35.030
-Maybe you should tell them
about the modems.

26:39.003 --> 26:43.038
-Oh, where do you want to
put him?

26:45.207 --> 26:48.340
-What the fuck is this?

26:48.375 --> 26:50.342
-That's a -- yeah,
everyone builds their own desk.

26:50.377 --> 26:53.851
That's -- that's a tradition.
-Yeah, I'm not doing that.

26:53.886 --> 26:57.756
-US Robotics pulled
out of the deal.

26:57.791 --> 27:00.055
-Told you.
What's our exposure?

27:00.090 --> 27:02.794
-Exposure?
-How much money

27:02.829 --> 27:04.191
did you spend on the modems?

27:04.226 --> 27:06.732
-Oh, $1.6 million.

27:06.767 --> 27:10.032
-One point what?!
-What?!

27:10.067 --> 27:12.837
-Spent $1.6 million
on materials and labor.

27:12.872 --> 27:16.203
-Where did you get $1.6 million?

27:16.238 --> 27:19.107
-I got a loan
from the Bank of Montreal.

27:19.142 --> 27:20.878
-Mike, come on.

27:20.913 --> 27:23.111
-Get me US Robotics!

27:28.756 --> 27:30.481
-S-- Sorry,
who are you talking to?

27:30.516 --> 27:32.791
-Yeah.

27:32.826 --> 27:34.925
[Modem warbling]
-What the fuck is that?

27:34.960 --> 27:39.193
-Oh, it's called a carrier wave.
The calling modem is a --

27:44.299 --> 27:48.334
-Hey! Get off
the fucking Internet!

27:53.473 --> 27:56.045
-Yeah.
-Mike?

27:56.080 --> 28:00.478
-I think it's Casey.
-Uh-huh.

28:00.513 --> 28:05.054
-It's going to be fine, no,
it's going to be fine.

28:05.089 --> 28:07.958
[Ringing]

28:07.993 --> 28:09.927
You don't get to talk
to our team like that.

28:09.962 --> 28:11.797
You just get to talk -
<i>-Mike!</i>

28:11.832 --> 28:14.129
-Hi. Actually, no.
This is Jim Balsillie.

28:14.164 --> 28:16.329
I'm the CEO here now.
-Co-CEO.

28:16.364 --> 28:18.969
<i>-Okay, Jim,</i>
<i>what can I do for you?</i>

28:19.004 --> 28:21.202
-I want to talk
about these modems.

28:21.237 --> 28:23.842
<i>-Well, there's nothing</i>
<i>to talk about, sadly --</i>

28:23.877 --> 28:26.042
<i>w-we can't accept</i>
<i>the defective product.</i>

28:26.077 --> 28:29.210
-Let's cut the bullshit here.
$2.5 million, all in,

28:29.245 --> 28:31.916
for the entire order.
<i>-Yeah. No, can't do it, Jim.</i>

28:31.951 --> 28:34.215
-Then I'll decimate it for you.
$1.6 million.

28:34.250 --> 28:37.152
And if you don't take that,
I'll turn around and sell them

28:37.187 --> 28:39.858
to Rockwell for even less.

28:39.893 --> 28:41.420
-That's negotiation.

28:41.455 --> 28:44.126
<i>-Okay, how about this?</i>
<i>We'll take the modems</i>

28:44.161 --> 28:47.096
<i>if you throw in the patent</i>
<i>on Mike's phone.</i>

28:51.399 --> 28:53.465
-What phone?

28:53.500 --> 28:55.973
<i>-I thought we weren't</i>
<i>bullshitting each other, Jim.</i>

28:56.008 --> 28:59.141
<i>We've been building our own</i>
for a year, we want M--

28:59.176 --> 29:01.110
-How long to build a prototype
of the phone?

29:01.145 --> 29:05.048
-The Pocket Link?
Yeah -- a year.

29:05.083 --> 29:07.248
-No, no, no.
A prototype, Mike.

29:07.283 --> 29:08.986
A shell
I can wave around in a meeting.

29:09.021 --> 29:10.515
It could be
a complete piece of shit.

29:10.550 --> 29:12.583
-No, it --
we're not doing that.

29:12.618 --> 29:14.992
-No, we're...
Mike's not doing that.

29:15.027 --> 29:17.357
-L-listen to me: US Robotics is
building their own phone.

29:17.392 --> 29:19.425
We are now in a race
to get this thing to market,

29:19.460 --> 29:20.899
and we are a year behind.

29:20.934 --> 29:22.263
So I don't care
what you need to do.

29:22.298 --> 29:24.298
Get these fucking nerds
to drop everything

29:24.333 --> 29:27.004
and build this fucking phone!

29:27.039 --> 29:29.237
What?!

29:29.272 --> 29:32.141
-Sorry, guys, um...

29:32.176 --> 29:34.407
My girlfriend tried to cash
my check this morning

29:34.442 --> 29:37.344
and it bounced, and she said

29:37.379 --> 29:39.181
I'm not supposed
to come in here -- allowed --

29:39.216 --> 29:40.886
I shouldn't come
in here anymore.

29:40.921 --> 29:44.285
And she agreed, I won't be
coming in here any longer

29:44.320 --> 29:47.321
until I'm getting paid.
-Whoa!

29:50.392 --> 29:54.493
-[Sighs]

29:54.528 --> 29:56.330
I can fix this.

30:03.636 --> 30:05.603
-Okay, Research in Motion.

30:05.638 --> 30:10.443
It looks like your account has
exceeded its overdraft balance.

30:10.478 --> 30:14.315
-Didn't they just deposit
a check for $125,000 from me?

30:16.319 --> 30:18.121
-Yes.

30:23.095 --> 30:25.865
-Okay. All right.
Um...

30:29.167 --> 30:33.598
I have a mortgage with you guys.
Can we pull that up, please?

30:33.633 --> 30:35.974
-Spell your last name, please.

30:36.009 --> 30:39.472
-B-A-L-S-I-L-L-I-E.

30:39.507 --> 30:43.542
-"Ball-SILLY"?
-"BAHLS-lee"

30:43.577 --> 30:46.611
-Anybody gonna miss this
red chair?

30:46.646 --> 30:48.646
-No.
-You're good.

30:48.681 --> 30:52.056
-Different guys,
different piece.

30:52.091 --> 30:54.960
[Door opens]

30:54.995 --> 30:57.193
-All right, everybody,
listen up.

30:57.228 --> 30:59.360
From now on, checks will be
coming every two weeks.

30:59.395 --> 31:01.131
You will come get them
from Shelly.

31:01.166 --> 31:03.265
This is Shelly.
-Hi.

31:13.244 --> 31:15.343
-All right.
That's you, Shell.

31:17.512 --> 31:19.281
Mike!

31:22.022 --> 31:23.989
-Me too?
-Yeah, sure.

31:32.725 --> 31:35.429
-Sorry. Who --
So, who is Shelly?

31:35.464 --> 31:37.134
[Intercom beeps]
-Shelly?

31:37.169 --> 31:40.137
-Oh, dude,
that thing's haunting you.

31:40.172 --> 31:41.600
-No, I'm motivating you.

31:41.635 --> 31:44.240
And don't call me that thing.
I'm your boss.

31:44.275 --> 31:46.077
-No. No, you're not.
-Yeah?

31:46.112 --> 31:47.540
-Get me John Woodman
at Bell Atlantic.

31:47.575 --> 31:50.642
-You got it.
-Wait, um, what are you doing?

31:50.677 --> 31:54.712
-We are selling the phone.
Mike, I need a prototype.

31:54.747 --> 31:56.483
-I told you, I don't --
-Mike?

31:56.518 --> 31:58.254
[Beep]
<i>-Connecting you.</i>

31:58.289 --> 32:02.126
-Guys, -we are over $1 million
in debt with no assets,

32:02.161 --> 32:04.997
no contracts and no products.

32:05.032 --> 32:07.329
<i>-John Woodman's office.</i>
-Hi, this is Jim Balsillie,

32:07.364 --> 32:10.167
CEO of Research in Motion.
-Co-CEO.

32:10.202 --> 32:12.697
<i>-One moment, please.</i>
-[Mouthing words]

32:12.732 --> 32:15.172
Okay?
-Yeah, I --

32:15.207 --> 32:18.340
-No! He said there's no phone!
-I'm not asking you!

32:20.443 --> 32:23.444
Mike.

32:23.479 --> 32:24.775
-Okay.
-"Okay" --

32:24.810 --> 32:26.612
wh-what do you mean, okay?

32:26.647 --> 32:28.581
No, no, wait. Wait a minute.
Wait a minute. Wait a minute.

32:28.616 --> 32:30.616
Wait, wait, wait a minute.
Wait a minute.

32:30.651 --> 32:32.618
<i>-John Whitman.</i>
-Mr. Woodman, I am about

32:32.653 --> 32:34.455
to make you insanely rich.

32:34.490 --> 32:37.293
[Click]

32:41.365 --> 32:44.564
-Mike does not agree with this?
-He just fucking did!

32:44.599 --> 32:47.468
-That was duress! Okay?!
You're manipulating him!

32:47.503 --> 32:50.702
It's obvious!
What do you want me to do?

32:50.737 --> 32:52.209
-Uh...
-What?

32:52.244 --> 32:56.642
[Low hiss]

32:56.677 --> 32:59.810
-So there's a reason
why your intercom

32:59.845 --> 33:01.647
is emitting white noise.

33:01.682 --> 33:04.419
It's because it was
manufactured in China

33:04.454 --> 33:07.092
by engineers who didn't care.

33:07.127 --> 33:09.622
And now every office
in the world

33:09.657 --> 33:12.328
has to suffer an annoying hiss,

33:12.363 --> 33:16.497
a blinking red light,
15 different power cords

33:16.532 --> 33:18.730
that are utterly incompatible
with one another.

33:18.765 --> 33:21.370
So we're not doing that.

33:21.405 --> 33:25.308
We are not just adding
to the hiss.

33:25.343 --> 33:27.475
I will build a prototype,

33:27.510 --> 33:31.677
but I'll do it perfectly
or I don't do it.

33:31.712 --> 33:33.811
-Mike, are you familiar
with the saying

33:33.846 --> 33:35.813
"perfect is the enemy of good"?

33:35.848 --> 33:40.488
♪♪

33:40.523 --> 33:44.525
-Well, good enough
is the enemy of humanity.

34:05.449 --> 34:07.416
-[Sighs]

34:15.195 --> 34:18.493
Shelley, get John Woodman
back on, please.

34:18.528 --> 34:21.760
-So I reach out,
hang up the phone.

34:21.795 --> 34:24.466
He looks up at me like,
"Are you ready to die?"

34:24.501 --> 34:26.402
-[Laughing]
-No, no, no, no.

34:26.437 --> 34:28.239
And I'm prepared to die on it.

34:28.274 --> 34:32.144
Right?
Mike steps in between us,

34:32.179 --> 34:34.674
brings the glasses down
and goes,

34:34.709 --> 34:38.810
"Bitch, I tell you, when we set
the goddamn meeting."

34:38.845 --> 34:40.350
And he backs off.

34:40.385 --> 34:42.286
-Oh!
-All right!

34:42.321 --> 34:43.584
Woodman wants to see it.

34:43.619 --> 34:45.454
We're going to
Bell Atlantic tomorrow.

34:45.489 --> 34:48.886
-Wait, what?
-New York City tomorrow.

34:48.921 --> 34:51.361
-But he said --
-You have till 8:00 a.m.

34:51.396 --> 34:52.758
-T-to do what?

34:55.433 --> 34:56.795
-So, you didn't call him
a bitch, did you?

34:56.830 --> 34:58.632
-Okay. Okay.

35:01.538 --> 35:03.571
Okay, new plan, everybody.

35:03.606 --> 35:06.838
We are all going to chip in
and build this thing tonight.

35:06.873 --> 35:08.576
Okay?

35:08.611 --> 35:13.317
♪♪

35:13.352 --> 35:15.220
-All right, give me
a Fillmore toggle switch.

35:15.255 --> 35:17.189
Give me 33PF, uh...
-Yeah.

35:17.224 --> 35:19.818
-I think it's like
something kind of

35:19.853 --> 35:21.655
like a hybrid of one.
So I like the...

35:21.690 --> 35:23.195
-I thought you were playing
"Civ."

35:23.230 --> 35:24.790
-We're back.

35:27.663 --> 35:29.729
-I've got something for you.

35:29.764 --> 35:36.208
♪♪

35:36.243 --> 35:42.478
♪♪

35:42.513 --> 35:45.316
